7. JFrog + IAM / OIDC	Passwordless auth using AWS IAM roles

Prerequisites
Tool	Command to verify
AWS CLI v2	aws --version
JFrog CLI	jf --version
AWS account	Console access
JFrog Cloud account	jfrog.com (free tier works)

Step 1 — Set Up JFrog Cloud (Free Tier)
Sign up at https://jfrog.com/start-free/
Note your instance URL: https://<your-name>.jfrog.io
Create a repository (e.g., a generic or Docker repo)

Step 2 — Configure AWS: Create an OIDC Identity Provider
JFrog must be registered as a trusted OIDC provider in AWS IAM so AWS can issue tokens that JFrog validates.
# Get JFrog's OIDC discovery URL (your JFrog instance)
JFROG_URL="https://<your-name>.jfrog.io"

# Fetch the thumbprint of JFrog's TLS cert (AWS requires this)
THUMBPRINT=$(openssl s_client -connect <your-name>.jfrog.io:443 \
  -showcerts </dev/null 2>/dev/null \
  | openssl x509 -fingerprint -noout -sha1 \
  | sed 's/://g' | awk -F= '{print tolower($2)}')

echo "Thumbprint: $THUMBPRINT"

Then in AWS Console → IAM → Identity Providers → Add Provider:

Provider type: OpenID Connect
Provider URL: https://<your-name>.jfrog.io
Audience: jfrog-oidc (you'll use this later in JFrog config)
Thumbprint: paste the value from above
Or via CLI:

aws iam create-open-id-connect-provider \
  --url "https://<your-name>.jfrog.io" \
  --client-id-list "jfrog-oidc" \
  --thumbprint-list "<THUMBPRINT>"

Step 3 — Create an IAM Role for JFrog OIDC
# Get your AWS account ID
ACCOUNT_ID=$(aws sts get-caller-identity --query Account --output text)

# Create the trust policy
cat > trust-policy.json << EOF
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": {
        "Federated": "arn:aws:iam::${ACCOUNT_ID}:oidc-provider/<your-name>.jfrog.io"
      },
      "Action": "sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity",
      "Condition": {
        "StringEquals": {
          "<your-name>.jfrog.io:aud": "jfrog-oidc"
